nto national legal systems. The book also explores the sensitive topic of 'Western' human rights and other rule of law standards in a Muslim world. It provides an in-depth analysis of the role of sharia in the historical and legal formation of twelve representative Muslim states, with a unique comparison of key issues raised by the 'Islamic awakening' of recent decades. In the preface Jan Michiel Otto goes to the heart of the prevailing environment in which Western discourses tend to oversimplify the substance and effect of Islam and sharia.Watch a clarification on the book by Jan Michiel Otto here.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0https://www.aup.nl/en/publish/open-access  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aIslamic courts. 0aIslamic law. 4aIslam. 4aLAW. 4aLaw. 4aPolitical parties and party platforms. 4aSOC. 4aShariah law. 4aSocial and Political Sciences. 4aSystems of law: Islamic law. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Human Rights.2bisacsh  aislam, Islamic law, law, human rights, sharia.1 aBerger, Maurits, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBuskens, Léon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDekker, Albert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEijk, Esther van, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarding, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKoçak, Mustafa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKöndgen, Olaf, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLau, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMir-Hosseini, Ziba, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabular